ğŸ”§ Step 2: Configure Backup for VM
Using Azure Portal:
Go to Recovery Services Vault

Click + Backup

Where is your workload running? â†’ Azure

What do you want to back up? â†’ Virtual Machine

Click Backup

Select your VM(s) â†’ Enable Backup

Using Azure CLI:
bash
Copy
Edit
az backup protection enable-for-vm \
  --vault-name MyBackupVault \
  --resource-group myResourceGroup \
  --vm myVM \
  --policy-name DefaultPolicy
ğŸ”§ Step 3: Trigger a Backup Manually
Azure Portal:
Recovery Services Vault â†’ Backup Items â†’ Azure VMs â†’ Click your VM â†’ Backup now

Azure CLI:
bash
Copy
Edit
az backup backup-now \
  --vault-name MyBackupVault \
  --resource-group myResourceGroup \
  --item-name myVM \
  --backup-management-type AzureIaasVM
ğŸ”§ Step 4: Restore a Backup
Azure Portal:
Go to Recovery Services Vault

Backup Items â†’ Azure VM

Select VM â†’ Restore VM

Choose recovery point â†’ Create new VM or replace disks

Azure CLI:
bash
Copy
Edit
az backup restore restore-disks \
  --resource-group myResourceGroup \
  --vault-name MyBackupVault \
  --container-name IaasVMContainer;iaasvmcontainerv2;myRG;myVM \
  --item-name myVM \
  --restore-to-staging-storage-account mystorageaccount \
  --recovery-config recoveryconfig.json
